This is best illustrated by an example:

```cpp
// default r/v policy = reference_internal 
py::make_iterator(begin, end);

// this one's still using reference_internal due to iterator wrapper caching
py::make_iterator(begin, end, py::return_value_policy::copy);
```

This would be due to handle caster being created just once:  https://github.com/pybind/pybind11/blob/master/include/pybind11/pybind11.h#L1140 -- which makes all subsequent calls effectively ignore the `Extra...` arguments. Doesn't looks like it's by design? I actually have a use case where I need to select between copy/ref versions of an iterator at runtime...

// One other very minor thing, it would be a tad nicer to have `class_<state>(handle(), "iterator")` instead of `class_<state>(handle(), "")` since the iterators appear as `< at 0x12312312>` in Python; same with `key_iterator`.
